[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \C7. With nothing else attractive, a low club from your length is a sound, safe lead against the spade game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 4\S needing ten tricks. Count first: five trump tricks in \S, the \HA, the \DK plus dummy's \DA, and \CA give ten on top, with extra clubs and diamonds available. Game is already cold, so the club finesse is needless — and East holds the long, strong hearts you must keep off lead.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \C7, a low card that looks like it could be from honor-fourth, but the plan holds regardless. Win the \CA or rise with dummy's \CK — do NOT duck a club to set up a finesse. Draw trumps and cash: five trumps, \HA, \DA-K, and the long clubs bring ten or more. Because East sits with the heart threat, the value of the safe line is that East never gains the lead. Count, draw trumps, and claim.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Ten tricks were ready the moment dummy appeared, so finessing in clubs offered nothing and a heart attack to lose. You counted first and took certainty over a needless gamble — exactly the lesson.}
