{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \S5. From your long spade suit with no honor sequence, a low spot is a fine, safe lead against this club slam.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 6\C needing twelve tricks, with clubs as trumps. Count first: five club trump tricks, the five top spades headed by your \SA-K-Q-J-T, the \HA, and the \DK plus dummy's \DA give you a big stack, and with diamond ruffs in your short hand you have twelve. The slam comes home by power and ruffing, so the trump finesse for the missing \CQ is not your priority — count to twelve first.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \S5, which looks like a low card from length. Win it, then cash your top spades, take the \DK and \DA, and use your remaining trumps to ruff diamonds in the short hand while drawing trumps as needed. Five trumps, five spades, the \HA, and two diamonds reach twelve. Don't go out of your way to finesse hearts toward East — that is the hand sitting with the heart honors, and you have your tricks without giving them the lead. Count, ruff, and claim.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Twelve tricks were there from the spade run, the trumps, and ruffing diamonds in the short hand — counting first kept you off the needless finesse into the danger hand. A well-organized cross-ruff plan; nicely done.}
