[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \HK, top of your \HK-Q-J sequence — a safe, solid lead against the spade game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 4\S needing ten tricks. Count first: once the \SA is knocked out you have seven trump tricks, and the \HA and \CA make nine. The tenth has to come from clubs, where you hold the \CA-x opposite dummy's \CQ-J — a finesse against the missing \CK. That finesse is not a free roll, you need it, so listen to the auction: East opened 1\D and West never bid a thing. The missing honors are marked in the East hand, the \CK among them.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \HK, top of a sequence, so your \HA wins when you choose. Draw trumps, conceding the \SA, then go after the tenth trick in clubs. Lead toward dummy and run the \CJ (or the \CQ): East holds the \CK, so the honor is trapped and dummy's club wins. You are finessing into the hand that opened the bidding — the \CK is marked there, so the finesse rates to be a near-certainty rather than a guess. Do not bang down the ace hoping the king falls; let the auction guide you.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Counting showed the hand a trick short on top, so one finesse was needed — and the bidding told you which way it lay. East opened and West stayed silent, placing the \CK, so you finessed into the marked hand instead of guessing. To finesse or not is a question you answer by counting; which way to finesse, by listening. Nicely judged.}
